<h1 id="z-axis-research">Z-axis research</h1>

<h2 id="geospatial-criticism-cultural-critique-3d-modeling">Geospatial Criticism. Cultural Critique. 3D Modeling.</h2>

<p><strong><a href="http://zaxis.uvic.ca">Use the z-axis mapping tool</a></strong></p>

<p><img src="assets/zaxis.png" alt="lg right" /></p>

<p>Z-Axis research is a mapping project that uses warped 3D maps to interpret modernist literature, rather than impose GIS-specific space on texts that predate digital mapping. This project’s z-axis method uses data from modernist novels to warp archival maps from the modern period in 3D. The results visualize the spatial experience of the modern city as represented by a given novel, considering marginal and incomplete perspectives on the ground, rather than top-down or totalizing views from above. This project was first conceived by myself and Katie Tanigawa, and is currently under development with the Modernist Versions Project (MVP), Implementing New Knowledge Environments (INKE), and Compute Canada.</p>

<video class="vid" width="80%" height="" controls="" poster="assets/zaxis_poster.png"><source src="http://axchristie.github.io/DH2014/img/zaxis.mp4" autoplay="" type="video/mp4" />Your browser does not support this video.</video>

